<TITLE> Israeli writer Oz wins top Spanish literary prize </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MADRID, June 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Israeli writer Amos Oz picked up one of Spain's top literary prizes on Wednesday for his work to find a solution to the Palestinian conflict and his condemnation of all forms of fanaticism. Oz, a 68-year old peace activist and former Israeli soldier, is one of his country's most popular writers and known for novels such as 'My Michael' and 'A Tale of Love and Darkness', which deal with strains in Israeli life and tensions created by the Arab-Jewish conflict. "If I have to say in one word what my entire literary work is all about, I would say families. If I had two words, I would say unhappy families," Oz said on Wednesday in a statement after being awarded the 2007 Prince of Asturias Award for Letters. The prize recognizes international excellence in fields ranging from sports to science. Oz helped found Israel's Peace Now pacifist movement in 1978 after fighting for the Israeli Defense Force in the 1967 Six Day War and 1973 Yom Kippur War. He is one of Israel's best-known proponents of a two-state solution to the Palestinian conflict and an outspoken critic of radical Islamist groups that call for Israel's destructi
